title: * Re: PMPS faulted again from random change in the reported photon energy
text: So it seems that one of three possibilities is causing these spurious faults: 1. Kact PVs are jumping to nonsensical values (plausible -- we have seen this before) 2. Dump magnet PVs jumping to nonsensical values 3. Calculator has some kind of transient behaviour Not sure how to catch this. I think the archive sample rate is too slow to catch these transients.

text: PROGRAM: SPEAR to BEAMS delivering 500mA to users with top-off every 5 mins. BEAMLINES: All open, except BL17. FAULTS: 1330 Pump 1 failure at lift station by BL10-2. Blue light on top of cabinet and red light underneath emergency stop lit up. Reset emergency stop, turned pump to manual, it faulted within seconds. title: USEG 13 KACT jumping * Re: PMPS faulted again from random change in the reported photon energy
text: See plot attached. The Kact PV for the first HXR undulator frequently jumps high. So far I have only caught relatively small jumps, up by ~0.0002 in units of K. Not certain how high of a jump would trigger the PMPS.

FACET plan: laser to 155 valve overnight.
text: Our goal is to protect the cathode from contamination. Valves 155 and 215 are in and bypassed to protect from downstream gunk, but there is some concern of off gassing from the new in-vacuum mirror. Jerry provided us with a strip tool file (jsy_injection_mirror_vac.stp) to monitor vacuum activity. If the vacuum starts rising we should put the mechanical shutter, let the vacuum pump down, then adjust the wave plate to lower the laser power before re-establishing. The power meter is broken, so use this table to determine laser power. http://physics-elog.slac.stanford.edu/facetelog/show.jsp?dir=/2022/05/03.02&pos=2022-02-03T20:13:45

title: VVPG 155 is now in local mode
Turned on all FACET magnet power supplies, trimmed all quads
Spoke with ADSO * Re: Alarm Channel 17: PLC heartbeat alarm
text: We are in an unfortunate situation where our written procedure does not reflect the fact that Linac West PLCs feed in to the alarm. I knew this ahead of time. The alarm corresponded with the GunB/Injector Pilz Int Chain A PLC faulting due to expected PPS work. Both the NEH and EBD-FEE PLCs were ok. The alarm went green when the Injector PLC heartbeat fault was reset. With the information above, I made the decision to not insert and disable the BTH stoppers (the channel was already green by the time I would have gone to do this). I confirmed this with ADSO P. Miller.

title: Gallery Paging Test Results from today
text: I did a test of the gallery paging system today with Rachel, and here is a summary of what we observed. Gallery paging is NOT clear in Sector 28 near VVS14 Gallery paging is NOT clear in sector 16 near VVS8 If you are actuating VVSs in those areas please make sure someone is staged locally in the field to help warn local individuals of an imminent cycle of the unit. All other sectors are OK. Additionally, we observed that if the person in the ACR making the announcement does not speak directly into the receiver, the transmitted volume to the gallery could be diminished to the point of possibly being inaudible. So please be sure to speak clearly into the phone receiver when making these announcements, also please do not use the speakerphone option to make these announcements.
